Add a DebugFilter class to weboob/tools/log.py

The browser2 filter debugging is an extra level of "Debug". Since python
logging does not support adding severity levels, we use the Filter class
to remove the lines by default.

Sadly, we cannot pass variable to filters (logging system does not use
the instance passed with addFilter method), so we use to write a filter
for each use case (today: only one...)

Update Python build scripts to use the print function

In Python 3, 'print' was changed from a statement to a function.  Using
the __future__ module allows scripts to use print function whether
running with Python 2.6+ or Python 3.x.  This commit changes as many
instances of print as I could find to use the print function and the
__future__ module.

Write all intermediate JS coverage files to a well-defined location

All intermediate JS coverage files are now written to
"build/test/coverage/web_temp/coverage_{pluginName}_{specName}.json".
Unnecessary configuration options for this path were removed, to simplify
test runner logic.

Since the "istanbul report" command expects coverage files to use the
".json" file extension by default, that extension is used instead of
the fictitious ".cvg".

Refactor client build for new style plugins

This change moves all web client assets *inside* the python package
using them.  This is done for two reasons:

1. The folder structure is the same between development and production
   installs.  This removes the need to automatically detect what
   environment we are in, which isn't generally possible in python.
   It alse makes including the web_client assets into the python
   packages easier to manage... it removes having to copy and merge
   directories inside setup.py.
2. It removes the need to generate symlinks to put web assets inside a
   single path while building.  Using symlinks causes many obscure
   problems with module resolution in node.  The plugin web assets are
   still simlinked into place, but these symlinks are managed by npm
   itself rather than externally.

All core web assets have now been moved into `girder/web_client` where
they will also exist in the distributed python package.  This includes
build and testing infrastructure, though the test infrastructure is
excluded from the published python package.

One of the more disruptive changes is the merging of the "application"
and "source" packages (released as `@girder/app` and `girder`).  Because
the web assets are now structured in a more traditional manner, there
isn't a need to keep them separated.  There is a second top-level npm
package named `@girder/lint`; this contains global linting (and esdoc)
dependencies that are shared between the core and plugin code so that
in place linting works inside text editors.

One ugly part of this change is that there no longer is a "staging"
separate from girder's source.  The primary problem with this is that
there can no longer be a "committed" package.json file because it is
autogenerated by `girder build` to inject the installed plugins.
Instead, there is a `package.json.template` file that is used as the
core package configuration without any plugins.  Our new npm publishing
step would have to rename this file to `package.json` prior to making
the release.  I don't much like this, but I could think of a way to
maintain in place development (with npm watch) while at the same time
avoiding creating symlinks.

* The warning contains a count of the number of people in the stream.

  / @everyone is removed.
* This only applies to stream messages and not private messages.

emoji: Migrate bugdown emoji to use sprite sheets.

This commit switches to use sprite sheets for rendering emojis
in all the remaining places, i.e., message bodies and composebox
typeahead. This commit also includes some changes to notifications.py
file so that the spans used for rendering emojis can be converted
to corresponding image tags so that we don't break the emoji rendering
in missed message emails since we can't use sprite sheets there.

As part of switching the bugdown system to use sprite sheets, we need
to switch the name_to_codepoint mappings to match the new sprite
sheets.  This has the side effect of fixing a bunch of emoji like
numbers and flag emoji in the emoji pickers.

composebox_typeahead: Rewrite code for handling modifier+enter.

We've iterated on this code incorrectly something like 3 times now, so
it's worth rewriting it with a lot of comments in a way that makes
sense.

The main actual functional change here is that modified key + enter
now is consistently the opposite of enter (in terms of whether to
provide a newline or send the message) in all cases.

Fixes #6489.

compose: Restore shift-enter to always inserting a newline.

This was a not-well-thought-through behavior change done in #6489; the
part that was actually a problem was ctrl-enter not producing spaces
anyway.

So we fix this, and also add a comment explaining why.

Fixes #6908.
user-groups: Add user groups in typeahead code.
refactor: new message content -> compose textarea.

typeahead: Remove check for impossible case.

The pre-matching that occurs before we even get here makes it
impossible for this case to occur, and it causes a test coverage
error.

eslint: Enable `no-extra-parens` rule.

Following sub-configuration is disabled:
                "nestedBinaryExpressions": false,
eslint: Enable `conditionalAssign` config of no-trailing-spaces rule.

typeahead: Add new functions for differentiating user groups and people.

We use these new functions in the message compose typeahead so that they
can also be used in a PM recipients typeahead with both people and user
groups.

typeahead: Insert extended mention syntax for users with same full name.

Fixes #374.

[third] Replace jquery-caret with newer implementation.

Apparently, there are like 5 independently developed jquery-caret
plugins, none of which are great.  The previous one we were using was
last modified in 2010.  This new one comes from
https://github.com/acdvorak/jquery.caret and at least doesn't use
deprecated jQuery syntax and has a repository on GitHub.

This plugin is way larger than it needs to be for what it does, but we
can deal with that later.

DRILL-1735: Have closing of JDBC connection free embedded-server resources.

Hooked up closing of JDBC connection to shut down embedded Drillbit, and then
fixed chain of bugs exposed by that:
 1. Added test org.apache.drill.jdbc.test.Bug1735ConnectionCloseTest.
 2. Hooked up connection handler in Driver to actually close JDBC connection.
 3. Released a QueryResultsBatch in DrillCursor.
 4. Reset DrillMetrics in BootStrapContext.close() (so stopping local DrillBit
    and starting new DrillBit doesn't yield "duplicate metric" error.)
 5. Checked cursor/row state before trying to retrieve value in DrillResultSet's
    column accessor methods.
    - Added org.apache.drill.jdbc.JdbcApiSqlException (for JDBC-level errors).
    - Added org.apache.drill.jdbc.InvalidCursorStateSqlException.
    [SqlAccessor, AvaticaDrillSqlAccessor, DrillConnectionImpl, DrillCursor,
    DrillResultSet, InvalidCursorStateSqlException, JdbcApiSqlException,
    DrillResultSetTest]
 6. Released vectors in DrillResultSet.cleanup().
    Added org.apache.drill.jdbc.test.Bug1735ResultSetCloseReleasesBuffersTest.
 7. Delayed last-chunk batch until COMPLETED batch in QueryResultHandler.
 8. Added nextUntilEnd(...) workarounds for fragment cancelation race condition
    to TestView and other JDBC module/subproject tests.
 9. Tracked open statements in orer to close at connection close (DrillStatementRegistry, etc.)
10. Commented out nextUntilEnd(...) workarounds for fragment cancelation race
    condition.
11 Miscellaneous:
   - Added some toString() methods
   - Adjusted some logging (e.g., "// log.debug(...)" -> "log.trace(...)".
   - Cleaned up a bit.  [DrillCursor, DrillResultSet, QueryResultHandler]
   - Added a few documentation comments.
   - Added various TODO comments.

DRILL-2565: Add some key "already-closed" checks, with test for future DRILL-2489 work.

- Created AlreadyClosedSqlException.
- (Moved JdbcApiSqlException to be subclass of SQLNonTransientException.)
- Created test Drill2489CallsAfterCloseThrowExceptionsTest for eventual fixing
  of DRILL-2489.
  - (Is partial:  Covers Connection, Statement, and ResultSet.)
  - (Is interim:  Most methods' tests disabled with @Ignore("...DRILL-2489...").)
- Added already-closed checking in key places, especially those that involve
  communication and could hang for a while rather than dying quickly (e.g.,
  Statement.execute...(...)).

(sapling split of 76e39de12cf22de68a6d7d8c8e18b5cee207509d)

options for more memory-efficient pex files

Adds always_write_cache option to PEX files (please suggest a better name if there is one.)  What this feature does is the following:
  if the PEX is a directory or (the PEX is compressed but always_write_cache=True):
     don't bother monkeypatching zipimport=twitter.common.python.importer
  else:
     monkeypatch

The t.c.p.importer recursive zipimporter needs to load all zip-based eggs
into RAM in order to use them, so that uses a bit of extra memory if any of
the eggs happen to be big (e.g.  mesos core.)

always_write_cache=True will dump all pexfile/.deps into ~/.pex/eggs first,
then relies upon the standard library zipimporter.

the motivation for this can be found at
https://jira.twitter.biz/browse/MESOS-3251?focusedCommentId=997079&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-997079

specifically, we were OOMing when launching the thermos_executor.pex in a
128M cgroup even though the steady-state RSS is ~50M.  turns out that we
were using >80M just to write mesos eggs to disk in order to launch.

(sapling split of 59d09733b3cad8341998fe1e0fe8ded815940064)

FIX: pants Ivy sometimes can't create symbolic links

When I was running pants for Java or Scala projects, I found that Ivy is trying to copy many dependency jars from ~/.ivy to ./.pants.d/classpath/mapped-jars even if we give -symlink option.

I traced the source code and found that Ivy is calling "ln -s" internally to create a symbolic link and after that, using File.getCanonicalPath() to make sure whether it is actual symbolic link or not. Unfortunately it doesn't work in very specific case, then Ivy just removes the symbolic link then copies file instead.
Here is a proof of concept why Ivy fails to confirm the symbolic links using File.getCanonicalPath() - https://gist.github.com/niw/6456578

In the Ivy code, it invokes File.exists() before making symbolic links, which eventually calls File.getCanonicalPath() and cache non-resolved path when we're using SecurityManager.
And, pants using Nailgun as default and Nailgun sessions are using NGSecurityManager which is inherited from SecurityManager causes this issue.

To address this issue, I gave -Dsun.io.useCanonCaches to jvm to not use cache when calling File.getCanonicalPath().

RB_ID=191093

(sapling split of 4db2a8f5c0f5ea6632ccee66bbab217ac9238c65)

Require java_library targets have either sources or resources.

Pants users often use `java_library' targets as pure aggregation
targets rather than the explicit `dependencies' target. Often
this is okay as a dependencies only library is similar to an
explicit dependencies target.

This causes issues when folks go to publish artifacts and find
out it doesn't work.

This change cleans up a lot of the "dependency targets incorrectly
defined as libraries" issue, and adds a check to ensure we do not
allow `java_library' targets to be accidentally used as aggregation
targets going forward.

Users with publishing issues simply need to stop using the
aggregation targets, which is guidance enough that anyone can fix
the issue themselves.

Pants essentials tech talk

Pants essentials tech talk slides.

These slides are generated with the Twitter University Courseware Development Kit (cdk) that's still a private github project. It generates a self-contained html file with all the javascript/images embedded.

The goal of this talk is to set a baseline of pants knowledge for the entire engineering org. Its targeted at folks who know what a build system is, know how to write code, etc. They just don't know how to use pants yet. So its practically oriented to get them up to speed quickly. Folks who are interested in learning more could take a followup internals class, but we won't subject everyone to that by default.

The tech talk would be these slides first, then this demo: https://github.com/traviscrawford/commons/tree/echo_codelab/src/java/com/twitter/common/codelab/echo

RB_ID=204476

(sapling split of e0e6c3dedf7e1907d497979f045cfdf805b9457e)

Add pants support for publishing to kerberized svn servers

Twitter has moved to Kerberos for SVN authentication - time for pants to update. Fortunately, Java does the heavy lifting for us.

A pre-requisite for this change is installing the "Java Cryptography Extension (JCE) Unlimited Strength Jurisdiction Policy Files". Since these do not ship with the JVM and are client-side JVM configuration files, this part is something every single developer will have to do locally. I'm open to suggestions on how to automate this if folks have ideas.

The JVM args are specified in pants.ini to pants itself stays flexible and can publish to any SVN type of SVN repo, regardless of what auth it uses.

REFERENCES:

http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html
https://code.google.com/p/ivysvn/
http://www.smartsvn.com/techarticles/configuration.kerberos-over-spnego

Pants input validation improvements

This change makes some improvements to pants input validation. Currently these errors cause pants to fail internally making the user think pants did something wrong when in fact the input is bad. We now throw TargetDefinitionException signaling to the user where the issue is so they can fix.

* Ensure target names are strings.
* Refactor AnonymousDeps into the targets tree for clarity and to fix the import issue.
* Restrict the types of dependencies InternalTarget can have. When walking deps ensure they have a resolve method.
* Check dependency types in JarDependency. Do NOT change the inheritance hierarchy at this time.
* Guard against bad pants() definitions.
* Tests.

(sapling split of daf2dde48d40169c502d99bb92225252361b5f9f)

Update invalid target check to ensure targets provide an artifact.

This change is motivated by documenting how to publish artifacts.
Looking at go/pantstips there's a lengthy section that mentions
all dependencies must be publishable, and some depmap | grep
workflow to identify what targets in a given graph do not have
a `provides` argument specified.

Rather than moving this tip into the sphinx site we can change
pants to provide a better error report, eliminating the need
for this depmap | grep workflow.

Specifically, before attempting to publish we check stuff that
needs published and ensure it has a provides argument.
If there's a broken chain we print a full report of what's wrong.
Currently we show just the item that failed, and you'd need to
keep iterating to find all targets that are not provided.

Pants task development class slides

Add a "Pants Task Development" class slide deck.

The general idea is there are three main audiences for pants classes: regular users, plugin writers, and core developers. Regular users take the "essentials" class to learn how to use pants as it works today. This class is targeted at folks who don't want to hack on the core of pants itself, but do need pants to behave differently than it does today. Those folks can learn how to write new tasks, such as a new type of report, new compiler support, etc.

Core developers do not have any materials at this time, although they will likely find the task development materials useful.

Giving this class is my hack week project, so the materials as not at the level I typically aim for. They're a good first pass and I'll use them as-is, and likely make a bunch of edits in response to student feedback from the three classes offered this week.

Push group handling into GroupTask.

This eliminates knowledge of groups from the core Engine
implementations and isolates their handling to a specialized
GroupTask that delegates to GroupMembers each producing the
same product type.

This also eliminates the trace of groups in every Task's
execute signature which now no-longer takes targets.  Tasks
instead get the targets they need from the context uniformly.

Finally, a prepare lifecycle method is added to the base task
interface.  Today this is called lockstep after the contructor
by the core engine, but in the future it will be where things
like product requirements are registered.

Highway to PSR2

PSR2 rules fully expanded into phpcs.xml, with all errors commented out and marked as fixable or as targets for warnings.

Removing `?>` from files with only php

"There MUST NOT be trailing whitespace at the end of non-blank lines."

When present, there MUST be one blank line after the namespace declaration.

When present, all use declarations MUST go after the namespace declaration.
There MUST be one use keyword per declaration.
There MUST be one blank line after the use block.

The extends and implements keywords MUST be declared on the same line as the class name.
The opening brace for the class go MUST go on its own line; the closing brace for the class MUST go on the next line after the body.
Lists of implements MAY be split across multiple lines, where each subsequent line is indented once. When doing so, the first item in the list MUST be on the next line, and there MUST be only one interface per line.

Visibility MUST be declared on all methods.

method visibility precedes static keyword and follows abstract keyword

(Mostly removing extra lines before closing braces in methods.)
Method names MUST NOT be declared with a space after the method name.
The opening brace MUST go on its own line, and the closing brace MUST go on the next line following the body.
There MUST NOT be a space after the opening parenthesis, and there MUST NOT be a space before the closing parenthesis.

In the argument list, there MUST NOT be a space before each comma, and there MUST be one space after each comma.

When making a method or function call, there MUST NOT be a space between the method or function name and the opening parenthesis, there MUST NOT be a space after the opening parenthesis, and there MUST NOT be a space before the closing parenthesis.
In the argument list, there MUST NOT be a space before each comma, and there MUST be one space after each comma. (**MOSTLY THIS**)
Argument lists MAY be split across multiple lines, where each subsequent line is indented once. When doing so, the first item in the list MUST be on the next line, and there MUST be only one argument per line.

Argument lists MAY be split across multiple lines, where each subsequent line is indented once. When doing so, the first item in the list MUST be on the next line, and there MUST be only one argument per line.

There MUST be one space after the control structure keyword
 There MUST NOT be a space after the opening parenthesis
 There MUST NOT be a space before the closing parenthesis
 There MUST be one space between the closing parenthesis and the opening brace
 The structure body MUST be indented once
 The closing brace MUST be on the next line after the body

The body of each structure MUST be enclosed by braces. **No inline control structures**

The case statement MUST be indented once from switch, and the break keyword (or other terminating keyword) MUST be indented at the same level as the case body.
There MUST be a comment such as // no break when fall-through is intentional in a non-empty case body.

refactor(ngModelController,formController): centralize and simplify logic

The previous logic for async validation in
`ngModelController` and `formController` was not maintainable:
- control logic is in multiple parts, e.g. `ctrl.$setValidity`
  waits for end of promises and continuous the control flow
  for async validation
- logic for updating the flags `ctrl.$error`, `ctrl.$pending`, `ctrl.$valid`
  is super complicated, especially in `formController`

This refactoring makes the following changes:
- simplify async validation: centralize control logic
  into one method in `ngModelController`:
  * remove counters `invalidCount` and `pendingCount`
  * use a flag `currentValidationRunId` to separate
    async validator runs from each other
  * use `$q.all` to determine when all async validators are done
- centralize way how `ctrl.$modelValue` and `ctrl.$invalidModelValue`
  is updated
- simplify `ngModelController/formCtrl.$setValidity` and merge
  `$$setPending/$$clearControlValidity/$$clearValidity/$$clearPending`
  into one method, that is used by `ngModelController` AND
  `formController`
  * remove diff calculation, always calculate the correct state anew,
    only cache the css classes that have been set to not
    trigger too many css animations.
  * remove fields from `ctrl.$error` that are valid and add private `ctrl.$$success`:
    allows to correctly separate states for valid, invalid, skipped and pending,
    especially transitively across parent forms.
- fix bug in `ngModelController`:
  * only read out `input.validity.badInput`, but not
    `input.validity.typeMismatch`,
    to determine parser error: We still want our `email`
    validator to run event when the model is validated.
- fix bugs in tests that were found as the logic is now consistent between
  `ngModelController` and `formController`

BREAKING CHANGE:
- `ctrl.$error` does no more contain entries for validators that were
  successful.
- `ctrl.$setValidity` now differentiates between `true`, `false`,
  `undefined` and `null`, instead of previously only truthy vs falsy.

Closes #8941
